After discussions with union leadership, we mutually agreed to offer professional development remotely for Wednesday 9/2 and Thursday 9/3. This time will allow for more preparations and construction punch list items to be completed. You should not report to the school for professional development. However, we will be offering COVID-19 antibody testing on Wednesday afternoon and Thursday morning during "Making Ready" time. We will have more details on COVID testing with a signup google sheet and Mr.Terranova will be providing the details on professional development shortly.

Professionally Yours,
Bob

post_text:
To All Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

As you undoubtedly have already heard, our beloved, long-time volunteer Eddie Kirker passed away Friday. I first want to thank Brian Leger who kept us all up to date about Eddie's condition during the last several weeks. Brian you were a special friend to the family and our community during this time. Our athletics programs and our Automotive Technology program as well as our entire school community mourn the loss of Eddie. In addition to serving our school, Eddie was WWII naval veteran, long time basketball referee and a member of the Chatham VFW. Eddie's burial will be on Thursday July 16, 2020 at 2 pm at Massachusetts National Cemetery in Bourne.

Bob Sanborn, Superintendent

post_text:
To All Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

This is your Superintendent, Bob Sanborn. As you may have already heard Governor Baker announced that Massachusetts schools will remain closed for the remainder of the school year. However, Cape Cod Tech continues the educational process through our remote learning environment. It is imperative that your student continue accessing their work and their teachers during this time for educational as well as social emotional reasons. As you know the last day of school is now June 15th for students and our amazing seniors last day is May 22nd! Cape Cod Tech's mission carries on...but online. We will be in touch over the next several weeks with information about end of year activities especially as it pertains to our seniors so stay tuned for virtual invitations in the near future. To our seniors, it goes without saying that we did not want your last year at CCT to end this way but your resilience and persistence during these challenging times has been inspiring. Thank you all...

post_text:
To All Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

I hope this announcement finds you healthy and safe. We have recently polled our faculty and parents and the overwhelming majority want to cancel April vacation to get out four days earlier in June. This afternoon our school committee met and voted to change the school calendar eliminating April vacation this school year. This means school will end for students on June 15th. I apologize for the short notice, so please reach out to our school if this change impacts your students ability to complete their classwork next week. Also keep in mind that next Monday April 20th is a holiday and there is no school Monday. Thank you, Supt. Bob Sanborn

post_text:
To All Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

This is your Superintendent Bob Sanborn. As you probably have already heard, Governor Baker has ordered all schools to remain closed through the month of April with a return to school on May 4th at the earliest. Everything we have in place for online education remains. It is essential for all students to check with their teachers via google classroom to keep the educational process going during this extended break from our school. Student participation and effort are mandatory and expected. Our teachers and support staff are going above and beyond to provide a online learning environment and we need the assistance of Cape Cod Tech parents and guardians to ensure your student's education progresses during this unusual time. While the school is closed, our staff is accessible to assist you via email and phone. Thank you and stay tuned in the coming days for further updates. Please stay safe and healthy.

post_text:
To All Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

This is Superintendent Bob Sanborn telling you what you probably already know. Governor Baker has ordered all non-essential businesses to close by noon tomorrow March 24th and stay closed until April 7th. He has also issued a stay at home advisory to all citizens. Cape Cod Tech will be completely closed to all staff until April 7th consistent with Governor Baker's order. However, the business of education continues online with our teaching staff, our support staff and our students. Students we can tell if you are checking in online. In order to stay safe and healthy as a community we must follow the Governor's advisory to stay at home other than for getting essential goods and services for your family. As with previous announcements please stay tuned as this situation is extremely subject to change. Thank you

To All Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

This is Superintendent Bob Sanborn. Although we do not recommend coming to our school for any non-essential reason during the closure, all our families and staff should know that on Friday March 20th and Monday March 23rd the building at Cape Cod Tech will be completely closed. No public or personnel should attempt to come to our facility. Once again, the building at Cape Cod Tech will be completely closed on Friday March 20th and Monday March 23rd with staff returning on Tuesday March 24th only for assignments that cannot be completed at home. However, staff will be accessible via email for families as we start the first day of online learning on Monday.

Thank you.

post_text:
To All Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

After a conference call with DPH and the Commissioner of Education and a meeting with the Cape and Island's Superintendent's at 11:30 this morning, Cape Cod Tech has decided along with a majority of the Cape Cod school districts to close school for two weeks beginning Monday March 16th to allow for social distancing to hopefully combat the COVID-19 virus. Once again, Cape Cod Tech will be closed for two weeks starting March 16th. We will update you in this two week period if the situation changes. All sports, meetings, events and activities are cancelled during this two week period.

To All Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

Once again, Cape Cod Tech will be closed for two weeks starting March 16th. We will update you in this two week period if the situation changes. All sports, meetings, events and activities are cancelled during this two week period.

post_text:
To Members of the Cape Cod Tech Community,

This is Superintendent Bob Sanborn. I just wanted you to know that you may hear from your child or in the community that we cancelled our Job Fair today here at the school. The cancellation was in response to Governor Baker's guidance to avoid large gatherings that are non-essential. As an administration, we are looking ahead at events, activities and field trips to determine whether they should be postponed or cancelled. Staff and students will be advised about these decisions when they are made. The situation is day to day but the likelihood of contracting COVID-19 is still "low" at this time. We are monitoring guidance from the Governor, the Harwich Board of Health and the Massachusetts Department of Public Health to inform are decision-making going forward. Thank you

CAPECODCHRONICLE.COM
Cape Tech Adult Career Technical Initiative Gets Attention Of State Officials

Community School at Cape Cod Tech
March 11 at 11:51 AM ·

In the presence of the Labor Secretary Rosalin Acosta, and Assistant Secretary for Career Education Bob LePage, and Superintendent Robert Sanborn, our first group of 12 HVAC trainees have graduated! Thank you to the Cape Cod Chronicle for covering this fantastic event last Friday in which these outstanding individuals received their certificate of completion and interviewed for open positions at local businesses.

We are incredibly grateful to the businesses who brought this program to our attention and spurred our decision to apply for and receive the funding from the Commonwealth of Massachusetts to offer this program to our community. Robies Heating & Cooling , Rusty's Inc. Plumbing, Heating, and Air Conditioning , Seaside Gas Service, Inc. W. Vernon Whiteley Plumbing & Heating

Our next session at Cape Cod Regional Technical High School begins in April, and we are accepting applications through March 16th!

February 21 at 4:00 PM ·

Jobs in the HVAC trade are projected to grow 13% from 2018 to 2028, much faster than the average for many occupations.

Our HVAC Training Program, starting in just a few short months, will train our students thoroughly in the art of heating and cooling systems. With 70 hours of hands-on training, OSHA 10 Certification, three full days of on-the-job shadowing, resume-building, career skills training, and guaranteed interviews with local HVAC companies, students will be able to jump immediately into the industry upon completion of the course.

Calling all aspiring nail technicians! There’s still time to apply to our manicure licensing session, starting March 15th! Completion of this course will prepare students for their State Licensing Exam, which covers table set-up, basic manicure, and tip application. This course also includes additional demonstrations outside the exam preparation, such as pedicures, wraps, gel application, and nail art.

We also have additional training hours available upon course completion! Learn more by heading over to our website and downloading the Manicure Program Handbook here: https://ecs.page.link/1dsis

We also have additional training hours available upon course completion! Learn more by heading over to our website and downloading the Manicure Program Handbook here: https://ecs.page.link/1dsis

We held our Senior Showcase today, and we couldn't be more proud of our seniors who worked all year on their final projects!

Some of this year’s projects included a computer integrated desk, a wooden boat covered in shrink wrap, 3D printed fishing lures, custom auto painting with metal flake, a beach restoration project for the town of Brewster, and microblading of eyebrows. Check out the photos! Which project is your favorite?

Great job, everyone!

Are you (or do you know) a 5th-8th grade student who is interested in learning more about what Cape Cod Tech has to offer? Begin your Cape Cod Tech story early by joining our Summer Camp program!

Beginning July 8th and continuing through the month, students can choose to explore a variety of trade areas, such as babysitting, cosmetology, culinary, design and visual communication, technology and coding, and marine services, plus boys and girls soccer for aspiring athletes. Join us for a few hours each day to see if Cape Cod Tech is a fit for you!

Learn more here. We look forward to seeing you this summer!

We are excited to announce that on Wednesday, March 13th Dennis-Yarmouth High School eighth grade students will have the chance to tour Cape Cod Tech during the school day and see firsthand the style of learning available to them. Students will be able to tour all of our 15 wonderful technical career programs that allow students to gain the hard and soft skills to help them be successful. We will also offer a presentation and virtual reality explorations of The New Cape Cod Tech opening in 2020! Students will be interviewed on this date as part of their application process.
In order to attend students need to complete the form found at www.capetech.us

Exciting news to share from one of our students! Jennifer Hollis, a senior in Health Technologies from Dennis, recently learned that her November story about student IDs won an award from the New England Scholastic Press Association! The Association holds a special contest on localizing every fall. The judges examined dozens of stories that took local, national, or international news items and localized them to their schools. Jennifer is one of a small handful of students to receive this award.

Please join us in congratulating Jennifer!

shared_text:
MA Army National Guard - Recruiting and Retention added 44 new photos to the album: MA SkillsUSA MRE Culinary Competition — in Framingham, Massachusetts.
January 22, 2019 at 3:31 PM · Framingham, MA ·

Today we partnered with SkillsUSA Massachusetts to host our first annual MRE Culinary Challenge! Teams from twelve local schools competed to create a full menu (appetizer, entree, dessert, and beverage) using only the contents of six randomly assigned MREs (Military 'Meals, Ready to Eat'). Among the judges were our own Lieutenant Colonel DiNoto and Command Sergeant Major O'Connor as well as Massachusetts State Command Sergeant Major Widberg. Thank you to all of our talented participants and staff for an unbelievable day!

post_text:
This year, our Dental Assisting/Health Education team participated in The Salvation Army USA Hyannis Corps' "Dress A Live Doll" holiday program. This program partners volunteer sponsors with children in need under the age of 12. The sponsors outfit these children with new clothing “from the inside out.”

Our students purchased many outfits including shoes, boots, sneakers, and new winter coats for their children. They also purchased toys and put together stockings for them.

Thank you to these students for helping make this a special holiday for the kids! We are so impressed with the generosity and charitable actions of our students, especially during this time of the year.

post_text:
Just before Thanksgiving, some of our Girls in the Trades students participated in the 6th Massachusetts Girls in Trades Conference and Career Fair held at the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 103.

More than 600 students, educators, union representatives,
contractors, and partners attended, representing 25 high schools and 33 organizations. Our students Molly Byrne from Plumbing, Alyciah Dias from Carpentry, Ivy Fanous from Electrical, and Marcella Larrabee from HVAC attended, and Alyciah was one of two students chosen as a student moderator. After her speech, the crowd gave her a standing ovation!

These young women represented our school with pride, and we can't wait to follow their success stories. Great job, ladies!

Cape Cod Tech Says Thank You
As we come upon Thanksgiving Day, we would just like to thank our students and families for all that you are and all that you do. We truly appreciate you.
We hope everyone has a pleasant Thanksgiving Break. Please remember school is closed Wednesday, Thursday and Friday.
Coats from our coat drive are now available for our students. The coats will be in the main hallway on Tuesday.
Harwich Junior Theatre will be offering a Teen Acting class at their theater beginning in January. This class could be free to students of Cape Cod Tech through a special access grant.

We're so proud of our talented CCT Horticulture students! Pictured here from left to right: Brie Talamantez, Chelsea Philbrook and Anthony Regnitto, showing off their floriculture and entrepreneurial skills.

These students make these beautiful arrangements and donate all proceeds to reducing students' transportation and food costs to attend the Future Farmers of America state competitions and career development events. They encouraged sales of $1 for a boutonniere, $25 for a table centerpiece, and $25-45 for vase arrangements. Coming soon: Thanksgiving and holiday arrangements!

If you're in need of some fall clean-up and help with yard work, these students will come to your house and give you a half or full day's worth of work. A team of up to 6 kids will arrive and help out with all types of outdoor landscape maintenance. Prices are $300 for a half day and $600 for a full day. The students will come with their own tools. Please contact Cassandra Madru at 20201648@techstudents.us for details and to get on the list!

post_text:
Want to know what our Marine Tech students have been up to? They had a chance to go over to Allies Aviation at the Barnstable airport to visit with 2010 Marine Services graduate Derek Golliff who is now an aviation mechanic as well as a pilot.

Derek spoke with them about his time at CCT and his career path in the aviation industry, showed them the engines, and pointed out similarities to the GX200 engines they had just completed in shop. He even let them check out the cockpit! We love visiting with our successful alumni to help pave the way for our next generation of skilled graduates! Thanks, Derek!

Inspiring meeting.
Rising Star- Harley Christensen from Cape Cod Regional Technical High School an amazing young woman in the Early Childhood program, who has written and designed a children’s songbook and
plans to go to Bridgewater State University.
We were joined by Steve Certa of the Weymouth Club who introduced us to Ilusion Faria who works on the Safe Passage program in Guatemala City. Safe Passage focuses on Initiatives to provide emotional and educational opportunities to women in the community including financial literacy and self esteem.
Listen to this amazing woman speak about this program

Have you RSVP'd for Tech Night yet? If not, great news. We just extended our "RSVP by" date to the day of Tech Night (November 8)! There's still time to secure your spot for dinner!

If you're a prospective student, Tech Night is the best way to learn about our academic and trade offerings, meet current faculty and students, and get a feel for the school itself.

What will your Cape Cod Tech story be? Please join us on Thursday, November 8th from 5:30pm-8:30pm for dinner and more information. We look forward to seeing you there!
